topic.title: Memory Mapped Remote Procedure Calls (MRPC)

body.p: The MRPC is a mechanism to allow hosts to execute procedures within Switchtec and retrieve results. Users can issue MRPC command via such four interfaces, which are listed as below. The module supports a single outstanding command per interface. The MRPC thread in firmware receives commands from each interface, and then check if the MRPC permission table of the interface. If yes, firmware executes them; if not, firmware return error codes. Note that only one outstanding command is available. See MRPC permission table descriptions of MRPC_DoS(Denial-of-Service) protection section in MRPC DoS Protection Settings the end of this chapter.
Switchtec supported MRPC command interfaces:

Switchtec's management EP contains a memory region which can be used to hold instructions and arguments. It also contains a memory region used to execute an MRPC command as well as a region used for storing output data.
Switchtec supports MRPC DMA Mode, where the command output data and status is pushed directly to host memory.

In a fabric setup, the MRPC command can be executed in both the local switch (attached to the fabric manager directly) and the remote switch (attached to the fabric manager indirectly via fabric link between switches). The MRPC command "Set MRPC switch index" is used to specify the target switch to execute the following MRPC commands, until a new “Set MRPC Switch Target” command changes the target switch for next MRPC commands. See the format of MRPC command "Set MRPC Switch Target”. By default, all MRPC commands to the fabric are executed in local switch.
The process for using the MRPC is as follows.

li.p: Write the input data parameters as defined in the command data structure into the Input Data region.

Write the command values into command registers. This will begin the command execution by the CPU. MRPC status will be set to 0x1 (MRPC_STAT_INPROGRESS) and the firmware calls the related command handler to process the command. If an unsupported command is sent, MRPC status will be set to 0xFF(MRPC_STAT_ERROR).

After the command handler is done, firmware will set the MRPC status to 0x2 (MRPC_STAT_DONE) and send MRPC Command Complete event to the host. The host should read the MRPC status value after receiving the MRPC Command Complete event, until it reads 0x2 (MRPC_STAT_DONE).
If MRPC Command Return Value is 0x0 (PMC_SUCCESS), read Output Data.

body.p: Input values are maintained in memory and can be used for subsequent MRPC commands.

note.p: All reserved fields defined in the MRPC command and sub-command input data definitions must be set by the host to 0x0 before MRPC command execution. Management hosts are not required to clear Input data bytes that are not defined in the MRPC Command definition for the command being executed.
No additional MRPC commands can be run while in MRPC_INPROGRESS state.

Since MRPC has only one input/output buffer for each interface, during the period of MRPC_STAT_INPROGRESS, firmware is using the input/output buffer. If additional MRPC command is sent from host, the input/output buffer will be overwritten and it will impact the previous command.
The context of which the MRPC command is used will be a single outstanding command per interface (PCIe Host/TWI/CLI/UART).

body.p: Input data buffer. Format is command-specific.
Output data buffer. Format is command-specific. Only valid when MRPC Command Return Value is 0x0 (PMC_SUCCESS).

It can be used to determine whether a command is in progress for the current interface, but will not indicate whether or not the MRPC thread is handling commands received from other interfaces.

note.p: Since all GAS accesses are handled by switch firmware, polling of this register will interrupt the processing of MRPC commands. Ensure that any MRPC command status polling logic does not flood the switch firmware with GAS read operations as this will impact MRPC command performance.

section.title: Event Notification
section.p: Simple MRPC commands are designed to execute quickly so as not to block new incoming MRPC commands. By default, the host will be notified when the MRPC command is completed.

section.title: Time-Consuming Commands
section.p: For commands that need longer execution times, a special command handler thread is called to process. Thus, the MRPC thread should not be blocked by long-running commands.

ol.li:
For those commands which need firmware to interact with hardware:
After completion, the handler may choose whether to notify the host or not. It depends on the command handler.
The command handler may just setup hardware, and tell MRPC how long it should wait. The host will then get the information from MRPC output buffer.

For those commands which just need to setup hardware, wait and then get data:
The command handler should create another thread to execute the time consuming action.
After waiting specified time, the host will send GET STATUS command to MRPC to get the final result.

body.p: The process for using the MRPC Normal Mode is as follows.

ol.li: Host write the input data parameters as defined in the command data structure into the Input Data region.

Host read MRPC Command Return Value.
If MRPC Command Return Value is 0x0 (PMC_SUCCESS), read Output Data.

topic.title: MRPC DMA Mode

body.p: The MRPC DMA Mode is used to avoid the potential high latency response for the Memory Read TLP from host side. In DMA Mode, Switchtec directly transfer output data to host memory and notify host with interrupt when DMA is done.
The following interface is supported in MRPC DMA Mode:

ul.li: PCIe host (In-band PCIe): one interface per partition

body.p: There are several fields in the MRPC section controlling the MRPC DMA Mode:
MRPC DMA Mode will be enabled after this field is written to 0x1.

64b PCIe address for the MRPC data buffer in host memory space, 0x810 holds the lower 32-bit address, 0x814 holds the higher 32-bit address. Host side needs to configure this address before the MRPC DMA mode enable operation.

This field is read-only, it indicates the MRPC DMA done message number, this field is configured in the configuration file field: MRPC DMA Done Interrupt Message Number. This Message Number is recommended to be different to the Event Manager Interrupt Message Number.

This field is read-only. Value: 0x1 indicates the switchtec supportes MRPC DMA Mode. Value: 0x0 indicates only support the MRPC Normal Mode. Host side needs to check this field to get whether switchtec supports MRPC DMA Mode or not.

section.title: MRPC Command Process in MRPC DMA Mode
section.p: This section will describe the sequences host side issues MRPC command to Switchtec side in MRPC DMA Mode.

fig.title: MRPC Command Process Steps In MRPC DMA Mode

section.p: 1. Host side needs to allocate memory for the DMA buffer to store the MRPC command header (16 Bytes), and the MRPC output (1024 Bytes). Header buffer contains the MRPC command status (4 Bytes) , Command ID (4 Bytes) , Command Return value (4 Bytes), Output Size (4 Bytes). Valid data in the MRPC DMA Output Buffer is indicated by the Output Size.

2. Host side reads the MRPC DMA Done Message Number (RO) (0x818) offset, then registers the interrupt handler for the MRPC DMA Done interrupt (can choose the polling Command Status for the MRPC DMA Done Event), configures the Host Address (RW) (0x810-0x817) (allocated in the step 1), Writes 0x1 to the MRPC DMA Mode Enable (RW) (0x80C) offset to enable the MRPC DMA Mode.

note.p: The initialization steps must be done during the host driver initialization process. There is no need to repeat the first two steps when executing MRPC command request sequences.

section.p: 1. Host side fills the MRPC Input (0x0) and Command ID (0x800) to issue the MRPC command as in the MRPC Normal Mode, Switchtec firmware sends the command to the internal MRPC handling thread. Note that host side should update the Command Status in the Header buffer to be Idle Status every time before any MRPC command request.
2. Switchtec side gets and executes the MRPC command. After the command is executed successfully. Switchtec will push this MRPC command output data directly to the host side's MRPC Output Buffer.

3. Switchtec side pushes this MRPC command Status (Done/ERR), Command ID (same as the host's written value), Command Return value (success or error code), and Command Output size to the host side's MRPC Header Buffer.

4. Switchtes side sends the MSI/MSI-X to host side if host side enables the notify option in Command Option (0x802). Otherwise host side needs to poll the Command Status (Idle change to Done/ERR) in the MRPC Header Buffer.

5. After host side is notified by the MRPC DMA Done interrupt or get status by polling to be Done/ERR, then host side can read the MRPC Header buffer and the MRPC Output buffer to get the MRPC command status and output data.

section.title: How to Read GAS in MRPC DMA Mode
section.p: During the interaction process between host and Switchtec, host side may need to read GAS to get some critical info. Switchtec provides two basic MRPC commands for this request.

topic.title: MRPC DoS(Denial-Of-Service)

body.p: The MRPC DoS(Denial-Of-Service) feature allows users to enable or disable a specified MRPC command executing via a specified MRPC command interface.
Users can define the total number of permission tables and their values via CHIPLINK. Each permission table contains selections for MRPC commands supported by the Switchtec.
Users can select a permission table id for each supported MRPC command interface via CHIPLINK.

note.p: Kayla: <TODO >Need to attach the chiplink capturing for mrpc permission control settings when chiplink is ready.

body.p: The Switchtec firmware default configure file sets 0(i.e. MRPC permission table #0) to MRPC command interfaces selection, and all MRPC commands are selected in MRPC permission table#0. That means all MRPC commands from all MRPC command interfaces are allowed to execute.
The CHIPLINK steps to deny executing Firmware Download MRPC command for MRPC command interface - TWI:

ol.li: Go to <MRPC Permission Table Settings>, configure <Permission Table #1>, de-select <Firmware Download> mrpc command name.

li.p: Go to <Management Settings>, and then <MRPC Permission Control Setting>, configure <MRPC Over TWI Permission Table>, select <Permission Table #1>

body.p: In the above case, if users try to issue firmware download MRPC command via TWI, MRPC command return value(0x808) will be read as 0x00064010, which means the MRPC command is denial.
